I believe that having more than one benchmark method would simplify both ConcurrentAccessBenchmark and ConcurrentAccessExperiment. For example:
@Benchmark
public Map<String, String> singleLockHashMap() {
    return this.single.doWork(new HashMap<>(), THREADS, SLOTS);
}

@Benchmark
public Map<String, String> stripedLockHashMap() {
    return this.striped.doWork(new HashMap<>(), THREADS, SLOTS);
}

@Benchmark
public Map<String, String> singleLockConcurrentHashMap() {
    return this.single.doWork(new ConcurrentHashMap<>(), THREADS, SLOTS);
}

@Benchmark
public Map<String, String> stripedLockConcurrentHashMap() {
    return this.striped.doWork(new ConcurrentHashMap<>(), THREADS, SLOTS);
}
Then, you wouldn't need the setup method in this class nor in the experiment class. You could also then remove the lockType parameter and wouldn't need a direct reference to ConcurrentAccessExperiment.

